Use **`WebApplicationFactory<TEntryPoint>`** from `Microsoft.AspNetCore.Mvc.Testing`. It hosts your app in-memory and gives you an `HttpClient` — no ports, no real server.

### Setup

```bash
dotnet add tests/MyMcp.Tests package Microsoft.AspNetCore.Mvc.Testing
```

### Example test

```csharp
public class McpIntegrationTests : IClassFixture<WebApplicationFactory<Program>>
{
    private readonly HttpClient _client;

    public McpIntegrationTests(WebApplicationFactory<Program> factory)
    {
        _client = factory.CreateClient();
    }

    [Fact]
    public async Task Initialize_ReturnsCapabilities()
    {
        var request = new
        {
            jsonrpc = "2.0",
            id = 1,
            method = "initialize",
            @params = new
            {
                protocolVersion = "2025-03-26",
                capabilities = new { },
                clientInfo = new { name = "test-client", version = "1.0" }
            }
        };

        var response = await _client.PostAsJsonAsync("/mcp", request);

        response.EnsureSuccessStatusCode();
        var body = await response.Content.ReadFromJsonAsync<JsonElement>();
        Assert.Equal("2025-03-26",
            body.GetProperty("result")
                .GetProperty("protocolVersion")
                .GetString());
    }

    [Fact]
    public async Task ToolsCall_InvokesTool()
    {
        // Initialize first (stateful servers need this)
        await InitializeAsync();

        var request = new
        {
            jsonrpc = "2.0",
            id = 2,
            method = "tools/call",
            @params = new
            {
                name = "my-tool",
                arguments = new { input = "hello" }
            }
        };

        var response = await _client.PostAsJsonAsync("/mcp", request);

        response.EnsureSuccessStatusCode();
        var body = await response.Content.ReadFromJsonAsync<JsonElement>();
        var content = body.GetProperty("result")
                         .GetProperty("content")[0];
        Assert.Equal("text", content.GetProperty("type").GetString());
    }
}
```

### Key points

- **`WebApplicationFactory<Program>`** boots your real DI container, middleware pipeline, and routing — identical to production, just in-process.
- **Override services** for testing (e.g., swap a database) by overriding `ConfigureWebHost`:
  ```csharp
  factory.WithWebHostBuilder(builder =>
  {
      builder.ConfigureServices(services =>
      {
          services.AddSingleton<IMyDep, FakeMyDep>();
      });
  });
  ```
- **SSE endpoints**: For Streamable HTTP (`text/event-stream`), read the response as a stream:
  ```csharp
  var response = await _client.PostAsJsonAsync("/mcp", request);
  using var stream = await response.Content.ReadAsStreamAsync();
  using var reader = new StreamReader(stream);
  var line = await reader.ReadLineAsync(); // "data: {...}"
  ```
- Make `Program` visible to the test project by adding to your server's `Program.cs`:
  ```csharp
  public partial class Program { }
  ```

This gives you full protocol coverage — JSON-RPC framing, routing, serialization, and handler logic — with fast, deterministic tests.
